# Day 6 - Triggers & SOQL

## 1. What is SOQL?

SOQL (Salesforce Object Query Language) is a query language used in Salesforce to retrieve data from objects.

It is similar to SQL but designed specifically for Salesforce data.

SOQL helps developers:
- Fetch records from objects
- Filter data using conditions
- Sort records
- Retrieve related object data
- Process information inside Apex code

### Example SOQL Query

```sql
SELECT Name, Email FROM Student__c WHERE Attendance__c < 75

## 2. What is an Apex Trigger?

An Apex Trigger is code that automatically executes before or after changes occur in Salesforce records.

Triggers help automate backend business logic when records are:

Inserted
Updated
Deleted
Restored

Triggers are commonly used for:

Validations
Automatic updates
Notifications
Calculations
Data synchronization
Example

When a student fee record is updated:

Automatically change payment status
Generate receipt information
Update student account

  
## 3. Difference
Flow vs Trigger
Flow	Trigger
No-code automation	Code-based automation
Easy to build	Requires Apex programming
Best for simple processes	Best for complex logic
Drag-and-drop interface	Written using code
Limited processing capability	High performance and flexibility
Used by admins	Used by developers
Before vs After Trigger
Before Trigger	After Trigger
Runs before saving record	Runs after saving record
Used for validation and updates	Used for related actions
Faster because no extra save needed	Used when record ID is required
Can modify record values directly	Cannot directly modify same record
Example: Set default values	Example: Send notifications

  
